name: 4-[(2,4-dichlorophenyl)(hydroxy)methyl]-2-phenyl-5-(trifluoromethyl)-2,4-dihydro-3H-pyrazol-3-one
source: Karthikeyan M.; Glen R.C.; Bender A. General melting point prediction based on a diverse compound dataset and artificial neural networks. J. Chem. Inf. Model.; 2005; 45(3); 581-2234
Reason: The compound in question consists of several functional groups and structural features that influence its melting point: 1) A basic phenyl ring generally has a high melting point due to its planar nature and stabilization via pi-electron delocalization. 2) Chloro substituents (2,4-dichlorophenyl) will tend to increase the melting point due to their electron-withdrawing nature which enhances intermolecular forces, estimating a +15°C increment per chlorine. 3) The hydroxymethyl group introduces hydrogen bonding, which usually results in a significant increase in melting point, estimated at +40°C. 4) A trifluoromethyl group is electron-withdrawing and also introduces bulkiness; this can increase the melting point by approximately +20°C. 5) The pyrazolone ring is a heterocyclic compound, which typically has a higher melting point due to nitrogen's ability to participate in hydrogen bonding and the rigidity of the ring system, adding an estimated +25°C. 6) The second phenyl ring contributes to the planarity and pi-electron delocalization, providing an additional +10°C. Combining these effects, the predicted melting point is the sum of the individual contributions over the base value of a simple benzene ring's melting point, which is approximately 5.5°C. Therefore, the overall estimated melting point for the given compound would be: 5.5(base value) + 30(2 Cl) + 40(OH) + 20(CF3) + 25(N-containing ring) + 10(additional phenyl) = 130.5°C.
